results.notes:
First 2019 fruiting of this species in my yard.
Large initially solitary specimen (another fruit body popped up overnight next to it) with large spores for this type, 10-13 × 8-9.5. In the past, I have measured even larger spores for collections made in the same location. Q values for spores measured from this mature specimen appear to be mainly within the range 1.2<Q<1.5, which is consistent with my understanding of rooseveltensis.
Stipe base buried nearly two inches in the soil.
Occurring in an open area where the only reasonable considerations for tree-association are a mature (probably 100 year old) shagbark hickory, and mature white pine. The latter is unlikely to be an associate, as A. rooseveltensis appears to associate only with hardwoods. There’s also a couple planted maples in the yard, but these likely play no role; even before the maples were planted this type mushroom occurred annually in this same location.
In-situ photos cover a 20 hour time period. Previous to the morning of July 4, this mushroom was not seen in this spot. (I have been checking daily.)

results.notes: This was an interesting observation. On June 7th I came across half a dozen polypores fruiting on the stump and buried roots of a hardwood tree that had been cut down about 5-6 years ago in a residential landscape.They were obviously in a very immature stage and I didn’t recognize the species at that time. I revisited the site and photographed the specimens periodically as they developed. They grew very slowly, but by July 1st I was able to photograph the pores and had a pretty good idea what the specimens were. This morning I took the final photograph and decided it was time to post this observation. These specimens have pores that are initially round and slightly angular. As they develop they become very angular, eventually taking on a labyrinth-like appearance. Mature pores measure 2-3 mm. depending on their shape. No part of the specimen bruises black even with vigorous rubbing and squeezing. Some clear, watery liquid could be squeezed from individual caps. Cap surface slightly velvety. Context very tough to slice. Following the thumbnail photo is a series of images (with dates) documenting the development of this specimen over a month’s period of time, plus additional photos of various features.

results.notes: Fruiting solitarily in mixed oak/pine woods, terrestrially amongst scattered rotting wood debris and leaf litter. Macro: Basidiocarp fragile; Pileus about 2 cm wide, small umbo (papillate?), smooth, chocolate brown, striate near margin; Lamellae free from stipe, whitish to salmon/pink, crowded, lamellulae present with inconsistent lengths; Stipe about 8 cm in length and 2 mm wide, glabrous, somewhat longitudinally striate at bottom half, pallid in color, with some slightly bluish tints, bruising somewhat greenish where handled (hard to determine hue of bruising and stipe in general, very low light and wasn’t sure if my eyes were playing tricks on me). Odor nondistinctive, did not taste. Micro: Basidiospores subglobose, smooth, a slight ‘pitted’ ornamentation or merely containing granule-like contents; hyaline in water with a slight yellow hue, with a more dominant yellow color in KOH & NH4OH, ~ 5.5 – 6.5 x (4.8) 5.0 – 5.6 μm, (L’ = 6.02 μm; W’ = 5.14 μm; Q = 1.07 – 1.30; Q’ = 1.17); Basidia subcylindrical to somewhat clavate to essentially club-shaped, 2 to 4 sterigmata present, multiple yellowish oil globules present, especially in KOH & NH4OH, ~ 20 – 30 × 7 – 9 μm, (L’ = 25.8 μm; W’ = 7.9 μm; Q = 2.5 – 4.1; Q’ = 3.3); Cystidia abundant, cheilocystidia & pleurocystidia essentially the same in shape/shize, cheilocystidia more abundant relative to pleurocystidia, broadly lageniform to somewhat mucronate and sometimes almost appearing subpyriform, more slender lageniform-ish cystidia also present (but not frequent), some cystidia with mucronate-like apical projections very common, ~ 23 – 50 x (4 – 5 -) 8 – 21 μm, (L’ = 34.6 μm; W’ = 14.8 μm; Q = 1.5 – 3.8; Q’ = 2.4) w/ apical projections reaching upwards of 8 μm in length and about 2 μm thick; Pileipellis a cystoderm of subglobose to ovoid cellular-like elements, up to 30-50 (60) x 20 – 30 (40) μm, didn’t find any cystidial elements in pileipellis, however, the mushroom was very fragile and 2 days old prior to micro (w/o any proper drying). No clamp connections noticed in any tissue/hyphae.

results.notes: Small fruiting on decaying hardwood debris, two mature basidiocarps and a few scattered pins present, arising from a mat of mycelium or possibly a crust-type fungi, found in mixed woods (pine, oak, hickory etc) in a lowland area with tons of scattered rotting forest debris; Macro: Pileus ~ 1.5 to 2.0 cm broad, broadly campanulate, dull and dry, somewhat velutinous, slightly wrinked at disc, becoming rugulose-striate towards margin, reddish-orange brown when immature, becoming a more lighter orangish brown in age, fading slightly in age before drying to a deep orangish brown; Lamellae subdistant, attached to stipe at apex, some forked at margin, interlamellar space venose, off-white to cream and somewhat concolorous with pileus near margin; Stipe ~ 1 – 2 mm thick and 4 – 5 cm long, finely pruinose to pubescent throughout entire length, even, pale yellow to whitish/off-white near apex, reddish-orange brown to brown below; Odor/Taste nondistinctive (did not taste); Micro: Basidiospores ~ 13.0 – 16.3 × 3.1 – 4.2 (4.6) μm, (L’ = 14.6 μm; W’ = 3.9 μm; Q = 3.3 – 4.4; Q’ = 3.7), narrowly clavate to subfusiform-elliptical, slightly curved in profile hyaline; Pleurocystidia not observed, presumably absent; Cheilocystidia abundant, made up of gloeocystidia, narrowly cylindrical in shape, tangled, intertwined, with and without pale golden contents near apices, exuding when lightly smashed to form plasma-like aggregated masses of said content, broom cells also found at lamellar edge, though basically absent (very, very scarce); Pileipellis hymeniform, consisting of broom cells with solely apical setulae, of which vary from cylindric and essentially uniform to conic, some irregular, pigmented with an amber to gold coloration, setulate ~ 2 – 5 × 1 – 2 μm, cellular body of broom cells generally clavate to cylindrical; Pileus trama consisting of interwoven hyphal elements, regularly septate, clamped, ~ 3 – 10 μm wide, hyaline; Caulocystidia abundant throughout length of stipe, irregular, ventricose to cylindrical, contorted, a bit larger towards bottom portion of stipe, with and without similar contents as the cheilocystidida; results.notes: Small cluster fruiting on small twig, amongst tree/leaf litter, lowland area within mixed woods (mainly oak, hickory, pine and sweetgum); Macro: Pileus ~ 1 cm wide, finely pubescent, translucent-striate, slightly plicate, margins somewhat scalloped/wrinkled; Lamellae concolorous with pileus, widely spaced, intervenose, adnate to barely sinuate; Stipe ~ 4 cm long and 1-1.5 mm thick, finely pubescent like pileus, concolorous with pileus and lamellae except for the base, of which transitions into a dingy grey, brown color (giving contract to white pubescence of stipe); entire basidiocarp pretty flimsy/fragile; Odor nondistinctive; Micro: Basidiospores long elliptical to cylindrical, monoguttulate or with granule-like contents, hyaline, ~ (7.4) 7.7 – 8.8 (9.0) x (3.9) 4.0 – 4.6 (4.9) μm, (L’ = 8.18 μm; W’ = 4.15 μm; Q = 1.73 – 2.19; Q’ = 1.7); Pleurocystidia rare, long cylindrical with a truncated apex, sometimes with encrustations or crystal-like elements present at apical tip, up to ~ 65 – 85 μm long and about 10 – 15 μm wide; Cheilocystidia abundant, mostly smooth, hyaline, thin-walled, extremely variable in shape, irregular, mostly capitate to subcapitate or sphaeropedunculate, though sometimes sublageniform to widely lageniform to narrowly utriform, sometimes subfusiform (very rarely resembling pleurocystidia with truncated apices and crown-like apical ornamentation), ~ 30 – 70 × 10 – 18 (20) μm (L’ = 45.1 μm; W’ = 13.1 μm), clamps sometimes present at bases of cheilocystidia; Pileipellis a cutis, elements consisting of septate hyphae, sometimes diverticulate, elements up to ~ 9 μm thick, with scattered band-like encrusted ornamentation (think pileipellis of Gymnopus and/or Marasmiellus), clamps present throughout; Pileocystidia essentially hyphal terminal ends (or at least appearing to be), abundant, hyaline and thin-walled, capitate to subcapitate, sometimes with various knobs (but not distinctly diverticulate); clamps observed in all hyphal elements.

results.notes: Two small basidiocarps fruiting from an oak leaf on the forest floor, mixed woods (pine, oak, hickory, sweetgum etc.), a relatively dense mat of mycelium present on the leaf, not positive if its related to these two mushrooms or not; Macro: Pileus about 1 – 1.5 cm broad, slightly campanulate when young, becoming more plano-convex in age, smooth to minutely wrinkled, whitish with a honey-colored disc (of which fades slightly), margin becoming slightly wavy; Lamellae adnate to sinuate, white, sub-crowded, lamellulae present, all edges becoming somewhat frayed (possibly in age/drying), but not serrated; Stipe about 4 – 5 cm in lengh and 2 – 3 mm thick near apex and about 1.5 – 2 mm near base, tapering downward somewhat, upper half smooth, white (concolorous with lamellae/pileus), with lower half becoming pubescent and light brown (honey yellow near mid-portion), base with white mycelium (near attachment to substrate); Odor/Taste odor relatively nondistinctive when fresh to somewhat farinaceous, becoming ‘sperm-like’ after drying (~ 2 weeks subsequent to collection/drying), did not taste; Micro: Basidiospores elliptical to somewhat pip shaped, hyaline, smooth, ~ 6.5 – 8.0 × 3.0 – 4.3 μm, (L’ = 7.46 μm; W’ = 3.4 μm; Q = 1.8 – 2.7; Q’ = 2.2); Pleurocystidia absent (or not found), gill faces only consisting of basidia (scarce) and basidioles; Cheilocystidia abundant, irregularly-shaped, some with various apical projections and some simply clavate, ~ 19.5 – 35 × 6.5 – 8.5 μm; Pileipellis a cutis consisting of encrusted hyphae, pale yellow 5 – 7 (8) μm thick; Pileocystidia scarce (or possibly overlooked), appearing irregular, branched, coral-shaped to clavate/cylindrical, (not positive if these structures were merely hyphae or cystidia); Pileal trama/context interwoven hyphae, hyaline and smooth, ~ 4 – 7 μm thick, Lamellar trama regular; Stipitipellis a cutis, hyphae hyaline to pale yellowish, 4 – 5 μm thick; Stipe Vesture/Caulocystidia irregular, hyaline and thin-walled, abundant, flexuous, narrowly clavate to cylindrical to variously shaped, up to 40 – 50 μm in length.

results.notes:
A single fruitbody growing near oaks and beech only a couple of yards from where the Tylo of obs 328145 was found last year. The two could be conspecific, but I am not sure. The one in the present observation looks more like badiceps (purplish tones in the cap and what looks like a nascent beveled edge).
DNA Sequencing Results & Discussion (posted on 27-Jul-22):
This collection was sampled for ITS by Dr. Kudzma upon my request. Two ITS sequence variants were obtained from one forward and reverse reads both showing one point of heterogeneity. One of the haplotypes inserts one extra “GC” unit in ITS2, so it’s a 2-base frame shift pattern. The two read are stitched together at the point of heterogeneity for a full-length joined contig. In addition, two isolated “Y” ambiguities seen in ITS1 in the forward read were resolved using the scrambled reverse read. The shorter haplotype has “C” at both positions, whereas the longer one has "T"s. The face-value genetic distance of the two haplotypes is thus 0.63%.
There are three accession in GenBank that are likely the same species — OM985884 (obs 323163), OM473836 (https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/56783911) and ON209210 (obs 212420). These are 99.2%, 98.9% and 98.4% similar, respectively, to Haplotype-1 and 98.9%, 99.2% and 98.7% similar, respectively, to Haplotype-2.
The two ITS haplotypes have been uploaded to GenBank and are posted here. Since I am not 100% sure this taxon is T. badiceps, I called them “cf. badiceps” in the accession titles.
Dr. Kudzma kindly shared with me the ITS and LSU sequences and pictures of his NJ collection of this taxon.
